arch:property.oc:show_val: Four bone tools. Flot sample 2 (4063), >4mm, 100% sorted, diagnostics only. This is a medium-large unit with light to medium brown bones. There is about 5% low temperature burning generally long bone fragments and foot bone. There is some digestion and a very small amount of polishing. Weathering is very uniform and very sight with only a few exceptions. There is little evidence for abrasion or rolling. Fragment size is the west mound standard - a number of pieces over 5 cm, but generally averaging in size around 3 or 4 cm. A little less than half the unit is long bone fragments. Upper limb, lower limb, ribs, vert, girdle of sheep/goat are represented in about equal proportions, but head and foot bones are predominant. There seem to be a lot of end splinters from proximal metapodials - this is particularly noticeable since most of the bones are not splintered. This may indicate production waste? Or butchering at joint - there are a fair number of distal tibia ends as well. Sheep/goat make up most of the identifiable bone but there is at least one dog, one cattle and several equid bones. There were also several human bone pieces that were recorded and sent to the human bone lab. They all appear to be intrusive, probably from the nearby burials. The unit seems very like a pit/midden with a mix of post-consumption and post-butchery waste. One fish vertebra, one infant bird bone and two frog bones were removed for future study. 4 bone tools, including 3 pottery polishers were also found in this unit. The flotation sample is generally light brown with well under 5% burning and only a small amount of digestion. There is no polishing and little abrasion. Fragment size is small with no pieces over 5cm. All the diagnostics are sheep/goat feet. It looks like dense fill or clean midden. Last Number = F273 F103 and F175 sampled for stable isotopes - CM/DCO 2010.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
